se communities being active often became a means to overcome the global, local and personal shockwave of the catastrophe and overcome feelings of insecurity. Yet, the broad variety of activities also furthered diasporic civil society and helped to integrate members of Japanese communities more into the surrounding society. By bringing together disaster studies and diaspora studies and analyzing the reactions of Japanese transient and permanent communities in Ghent, Brussels, Dusseldorf, Sao Paulo, Honolulu and London following the Triple Disaster, this volume will help to get a better understanding of how catastrophes effect diasporic communities.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 25. Feb 2021) 4aFukushima. 4aJapan. 4aJapanese communities. 4aTriple Disaster. 4adiasporic civil society. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  aAndreas Niehaus.  aChristian Tagsold.  aHeinrich-Heine-Universität Düsseldorf.  aJapan.  aJapanese diaspora communities.  aJapanforschung.  aJutta Teuwsen.  aKultur- und Sozialwissenschaftliche Japanforschung.  aNiko Besnier.  aPeter Bernardi.  aRuth Martin.  aTine Walravens.  adiaspora studies.  adisaster studies.1 aBernardi, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBesnier, Niko, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMartin, Ruth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNiehaus, Andreas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNiehaus, Andreas, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aTagsold, Christian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/rel